It's the early 1950s, and Arthur Freed is looking for something to pour his 1920s-30s songwriters catalog into.  The end result sprung out on American theatergoers in 1952 as "Singing in the Rain."  This song, Good Morning, was sung by Debbie Reynolds, Donald O'Conner, and Gene Kelley.  It was a musical and cultural phenomenon at the time, and still plays well.  The film's premise concerns the time of transition in the late 1920s between silent films and the 'talkies.'  How appropriate Gaga would pick up this theme, as her catalog represents one transition in music to another.

Just like with Tony Bennett, she is able to capture the emotive sound of a bygone generation--and not just a blaise cover.  Oh, good stuff and the work of an artist.  Perhaps le chanteuse?

Here is a link to the original.  Performance art on the national level does not have anyone of this stature and ability these days.  We must look for the gems.
